{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601718/1938030501/0228.xml":{"full_text":"George Vass of Washington\nCites Great Need at A.\nB. A. Session.\nBy EDWARD C. STONE.\nSpeaking at the annual Spring\nRavings Conference of the American\nBankers' Association in New York\nyesterday afternoon, George O. Vass,\nvice presiaem\nand cashier of\nthe Riggs Na\ntional Bank, de\nclared that every\nbank, whether it\nchooses or not,\nmust have a pub\nlic relations pol\nicy. It would\nseem to be the\npart of wisdom\nhe said, to at\ntempt a con\nstructive and\npositive attitude,\nrather than to\npursue the easier\nGeorie O. Vasa.\ncourse of allowing public relations to\ntake care of themselves.\nIt has been recognized that banks\nhave lagged far behind our public\nutility, industrial and merchandising\norganizations in developing scientific\nmethods for meeting their public\nrelations problems, he continued.\nThis may be due partly to some im\npression that the attainment of sat\nisfactory results in such a program\ncalls for the services of a high-sal\naried public relations expert.\nFortunately, there are several ap\nproaches to the main objective, and\nsome\u2014publicity, for example\u2014do re\nquire special aptitude and training,\nsuch as would not ordinarily come\nwithin the experience of the average\nbank officer. Constructive customer\nrelations, on the other hand, with the\naid of studies now available, offers an\napproach to the problem with rea\nsonable promise of success through\nthe use of the talent available in all\nbanks, and with little or no expense,\nMr. Vass said.\nBankers can ill afford to ignore the\npublic's attitude in this day, when\ndemocratic institutions are under at\ntack throughout the world. Whatever\nhappens to banking in the future will\nbe largely determined by public opin\nion, and that opinion in turn will\nreflect to a great extent the under\nstanding and reactions of our cus\ntomers.\nIt has been stated recently that\nthere are 44.000.000 savings depos\nitors in this country. These are the\ncitizens who continue, to practice\nthrift in spite of the new philosophy\nof \"spending.\u201d They are the back\nbone of this great democracy, and\ntheir hopes and aspirations, are de\npendent on its preservation. The\nbanks have helped these people in\ntheir struggle for economic independ\nence, and it is our responsibility to\ngive them the understanding to pro\ntect their interests, the Washington\nbanker concluded.\nRevival of Thrift Urged.\nAt the same conference Dr. Marcus\nNadler, New York University, urged\nbankers to \u2018\u2018reinstill the desire for\nthrift\u201d in the people so the building\nof the Nation ma; go on.\nTo house the people of the United\n6tates properly, in accordance with\nthe American standard of living, bil\nlions of dollars will have to be spent.\nThis money will have to come out of\ntfie savings of the people.\nTo promote thrift, he held, the\nsmall saver must be assured that the\npurchasing power of his savings will\nnot decrease materially.\nStanley M. Isaacs, president of the\nBorough of Manhattan, New York\nCity, speaking in support of Govern\nment financing of housing for lower\nincome groups, contended such con\nstruction, \u2018\u2018properly safeguarded and\nunder proper circumstances,\u201d would\nnot adversely affect private enterprise.\nHe pointed to England's combined\ngovernment and private housing oper\nations in recent years as a precedent\nfor what might be done in this\n\u2022ountry.\nSalesmen Meet In District.\nDistrict sales managers and other\nrepresentatives of Servel, Inc., from\nall over the South met here today at\nthe Hamilton Hotel and made plans\nfor extensive spring and summer sell\ning activities.\nGeorge S. Jones, jr\u201e vice president\nand general sales manager of the com\npany, led the discussions, and Roderic\nPeters of Washington, regional sales\nmanager, presided. Lew E. Libby,\nLe Roy G. Ehret, W. W. Wallace and\nF. S. Reid, all of the Washington of\nfice, also took part in the program.\nPour other officials from the head\noffice, Evansville, Ind., were here,\nas were salesmanagers from as far\nSouth as Jacksonville, Nashville and\nBirmingham. The visitors expressed\noptimism on the business outlook.\nDistrict Resident Promoted.\nR. S. Agee, for the past three years\nin charge of utility and dealer sales\ntraining and promotion for the Wash\nington Gas Light Co., has been ap\npointed promotional sales manager\nfor the Association of Gas Appliance\nand Equipment Manufacturers and\nwill assume his new duties in New\nYork on April l. Borp in the heart\nof the natural gas fields in Oklahoma\nin 1906 Mr. Agee's earliest mer\nchandising experience was as a sales\nman of ranges and space heaters in\nthat section.\nPrimm Wins Field Honors.\nPaul H. Primm, president of the\nDistrict of Columbia Life Under\nwriters\u2019 Association, has qualified for\nmembership in the Field Club of the\nMutual Life Insurance Co. of New\nYork, for the meeting in San Francisco\nin June. Mr. Primm has been as\nsociated with the Washington agency,\nof which Thomas P. Morgan, jr\u201e is\nmanager, since 1924 and has won this\nsalesmanship honor nine times.\nTelephone Calls Increase.\nThe number of telephones in the\nBell System reached a new all-time\nhigh in 1937. At the end of the year\nthere were 15,332,000 telephones in\nservice as compared with the*previous\nmaximum number of 15,193,000\nwhich was reached in 1930. The in\ncrease of 878,400 telephones in 1937\nwas 2,100 less than the increase of\n880,500 in 1936.\nThe average dally number of tele\nphone conversations during the year\nwas 68,790,000. There were 6 per\ncent more local conversations and\n8 per cent more toll and long-distance\nconversations than in 1936.\nSHINGLE OUTPUT LAGS.\nProduction of red cedar shingles\ntotaled 232,052 squares in January,\ncompared with 273,524 in the same\nmonth a year ago, the Census Bureau\nsays. t\nTRANSACTIO