 13% Young Sprg&Wire.. 3 15% 15% 15%-%\n43% 31% Ygstwn Sheet T.. 13 37% 36% 36%\n22% 15 Ygstwn Stl Dr .25a. 3 18% 18 18%-%\n17% 12 Zenith Radio_ 7 14% 14% 14%\nApproximate Sales of Stocks on the N. Y. Stock Exchange.\n11:00 A.M.- 110.000 12:00 Noon_ 220,000\na Actual sales: unit of trading 10 shares.\nx Ex dividend, xr Ex rights a Also extra or extras, h 1-10\nshare of 82 preference stock, d 1-25 share of S3 preference\nstock, e Declared or paid so far this year, f Payable In stock,\ng Paid last year, h Cash or stock, k Accumulated dividend paid\nor declared this year\nr In bankruptcy or receivership or being reorganized under\nBankruptcy Act. or securities assumed by such companies.\nRates of dividends in the foregoing table are annual dis\nbursements based on the last Quarterly or semi-annual declara\ntion Unless otherwise noted special or extra dividends are not\nincluded.\nCOTTON DEPRESSED\nBY BOMBAY DROP\nFutures Uneven in Range\nof About $1 a Bale\nDuring Week.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, March 5.\u2014Irregular\nfluctuations over a range of about $1\na bale characterized trading in cotton\nduring the last week. An early week\nrecovery of most of the recent lasses\nwas not maintained when foreign mar\nkets turned easier.\nMay contracts, which had sold off\nfrom a recent high point of 9.33 to\n9.07 and then recovered to 9.27, closed\nyesterday at 9.06, compared with 9.18\na week ago.\nThe widening of the spread between\nthe Bombay and New York markets\nwas closely watched. Yesterday the\ndiscount for broach April-May at\nBombay had declined to the equivalent\nof 78 American points under May here,\nthe widest parity since last August\nand compared with a December spread\nof 10 points. Traders here feared that\nlong contracts held here by Bombay\ninterests against sales in the Indian\nmarket would be liquidated at the\nmore profitable differences caused by\ndeclines at Bombay. Although Bom\nbay houses sold here, the total volume\nof offerings was smaller than antici\npated.\nQuiet conditions prevailed in both\nthe cotton goods and Southern spot\ncotton markets. With loans by the\nCommodity Credit Corp. on the\u2019 1937\ncrop ending March 31, the trade is\nwatching the movement of cotton into\nthe loan, especially for any sizeable\nquantities privately financed which\nmay be transferred to the Government\nloan.\nCHICAGO LIVE STOCK.\nCHICAGO. March 5 (!P> (United States\nDepartment of Agriculture).\u2014Hogs. 4.000.\nincluding .2.500 direct: steady with Fri\nday\u2019s average; few loads good and choice\n20()-2oft-pound butchers. 9.05-75; shippers\ntook 150; estimated holdovers. 500; com\npared week ago, weights below 200 pounds\n50-05 higher: 200 pounds up. 05-1.00\nhigher: packing sows. 05-85 nieher.\nCattle. 500: calves, none; compared Fri\nday last W'eek: Strictly good and choice\nmedium wpight and heavy steers. 25-50\nhigher; medium grade heavies, yearlings\nand light steers strong to 25 up heifers\n2o-4o higher; beef cows and bulls. 25\nhigher: cutter grade cows strong to 15\nup: vealers. 50 lower: very active market\nuntil extreme close, when price levels and\ngeneral undertone weakened: well-finished\nyearlings and light steers scarce, but heavy\nsteers in liberal supply: shippers and order\nbuyers a boosting factor in general market:\nbulk heifers comprised medium to good\ngrades: during last two weeks live market\nhas gained faster than dressed trade: ex\ntreme top heavy steers 10.25: several\nloads, lo.oo-lo.l5: numerous load heavies.\n8.75-9.75: best yearlings 9.7ft: best light\nyearling steers. 9.40: choice heavy heifers\nto 8.75: light kinds. 8.50.\nSheep. .2.000. including 900 directs.\nLate Friday wooled lambs active, spots. 10\n15 higher; top. 9.95: bulk. 8.90-9.15:\nchoice 100-104-pound weights 8.90-9.00.\nFor week ending Friday. 5.10o directs.\nCompared Friday last week, fat lambs. 50\n75 higher, sheep. 25-50 up: yearlings and\nfeeding lambs scarce: week\u2019s top slaughter\nlambs. 9.55 paid late by shipping inter\nests. closing bulk 8 90-9.15. with choice\n100-104-pound averages 8.90-9.on: week s\nbulk. 8.50-9.15: top clipped lambs. 8.10.\nbulk. 7.75-8.10: slaughter ewes mostly\n4.40-5.00: few choice GG-pound feeding\nlambs. 7.50.\nFOREIGN EXCHANGES.\nNEW YORK. March 5 OP).\u2014Major Eu\nropean currencies showed only minor\nchanges in terms of the dollar today\nThe pound sterling lost of a cent, and\nthe French franc dropped .00% of a\ncent. The Swiss franc gained .00% of\na cent and the milder .01 of a cent. The\nbelea lost .01 of a cent.\nThe Japanese yen touched a new 1038\nlow at 28.08\nLate morning rates follow:\nGreat Britain in dollars, others in cents.\nGreat Britain, demand. 5.01'A: cables.\n5.01%: HO-day bills. 5.00%; France, de\nmand. 3.25%; cables. 3.25%; Italy, de\nmand. 5.26%; cables. 5.20%.\nDemands\u2014Belgium. 16.05: Germany,\nfree. 40.45; registered. 20.60; travel.\n24.85: Holland. 55.91: Norway. 25.19\nSweden. 25.83: Denmark. 22.39: Finland\n2.21: Switzerland. 2.3.20%; Spain un\nquoted: Portugal, 4.55: Greece. .92: Po\nland. 19.00: Czechoslovakia. .3.51%: Yugo\nslavia. 2.35: Austria 18.95n; Hungary.\n19.95; Rumania. .74%: Argentina. 33.43n:\nBrazil (free). 5.90n; Tokio. 28.98; Shan\nghai. 29.76; Hong Kong, 31 40: Mexico\nCity. ,27 SO: Montreal in New York.\n99.98,\u2019,; New York in Montreal. 100.01,\u2022,\nn\u2014Nominal.\nSHORT-TERM SECURITIES.\n(Reported by Smith. Barney Ac Co.)\nAmer Tel A Tel 5s \u201943 _ 113% n3%\nAuburn Auto Co 4%s '39 21% 34\nAustin AC Northwest 5s '41 _ 85 88\nBaldw Loco Works 5s '40 _ 100%\nCalif Packing Coro 5s '40 _ 10.3\u2019, 104%\nCentral Foundry 6s '41 _ 98\nChesap Ohio Ry 5s '39 104% 105\nContainer Corp 5s '43 87% 88\nCuba North Rwys 5%s '42 35% 3R\nDelaware A- Hudson 4s '4.3 50% 5\"%\nEdison Elec Ilium 4s '39 02% 106\u2019,\nGen Public Service 5%s '39 9914\nGrand Rap A Ind 4%s'41 106%\nHouston Oil 5s '40 101 101%\nIllinois Steel 4%s '40 107V, 107%\nJnt Merc Marine 6s '41 48 50'4\nInt Tel Ac Tel 4%s