sports, amounting to $274,000.\nUnfilled orders as of February 28,\n1938, amounted to $6,200,000.\nCatalin Corp. of America.\u20141937\ncommon share earnings were 17 cents,\nagainst 52 cents.\nBabcock Wilcox Co.\u2014Declared a\ndividend of 25 cents, payable April 1\nto holders of record March 19. In\n1937 five dividends of $1 each were\ndisbursed. Company expects to sus\ntain a loss from operations in first\nhalf of 1938. 1937 common share\nearnings were $8.06, against $5.41.\nCase (J. I.) Co.\u2014Company proposes\nreduction in authorized preferred\nstock from 200.000 shares to 101,825\nshares and increase in common stock\nfrom 200,000 to 300,000 shares.\nFairbanks, Morse Co.\u20141937 net\nincome was $2,148,443, against $2,252,\n941.\nHobart Mfg. Co.\u20141937 class B share\nearnings were $2.73, against $3.01.\nIntertype Corp.\u20141937 common share\nearnings before surtax were $1.44.\nagainst $1.42.\nStarrett (L. S.) Co.\u2014Common share\nearnings six months ended December\n31 were $2.15,'agaifist $2.15.\nChilds Co.\u2014President said the first\ntwo months of year have been profit\nless for the company. He stated that\nit is impossible to tell when directors\nwill consider payment on account of\naccumulated preferred dividends.\nNational Tea Co.\u20141937 deficit was\n$1,365,280, against net income of\n$226,750.\nSears, Roebuck Co.\u2014Sales four\nweeks ended February 26 were off 1.9\nper cent.\nButte Copper Zinc Co.\u20141937\ncommon share earnings before deple\ntion were 17 cents, against 5 cents.\nInternational Cellucotton Products\nCo.\u20141937 Common share earnings\nwere $2.78, against $3.14.\nPacific Western Oil Corp.\u20141937\ncommon share earnings before surtax\nwere $1.45. against $1.62.\nSouth Penn Oil Co.\u20141937 common\nshare earnings were $4.64, against\n$3.59.\nLoews. Inc.\u2014Declared 50 cents\ncommon dividend, payable March 31\nto holders of record March 12. On\nMarch 31, 1937, company paid divi\ndend of 50 cents and extra of 50 cents.\nMorris (Philip) Co.. Ltd.. Inc.\u2014\nIt is said company is negotiating with\nLehman Bro. to underwrite an issue\nof $7,500,000 convertible stock, the\nproceeds of which would be used\nmainly to retire bank loans.\nNew York Telephone Co.\u2014Net sta\ntion gain February totaled 1,767,\nagainst 11,512 in February, 1937. In\ntwo months net station gain was\n5,002, against 24.211.\nFord Motor Co. of Canada. Ltd.\u2014\nProduction of this company in 1937\nis reported to have totaled 73,000 tars,\nagainst 59,971 in 1936.\nFisk Rubber Corp.\u20141937 common\nshare earnings were 28 cents, against\n7 cents.\nJohns-Manville Corp.\u20141937 com\nmon share earnings were $5.80, against\n$5.13.\nKalamazoo Stove Furnace Co.\u2014\n1937 common share earnings were\n$3.05, against $3.59.\nCanadian Industries, Ltd.\u20141937\ncommon share earnings were $7.86,\nagainst $6.45.\nMcGraw Electric Co.\u20141937 com\nmon share earnings were $2, against\n$2.13.\nDome Mines, Ltd.\u2014Bullion produc\ntion in February totaled $601,372,\nagainst $617,483.\nReed Roller Bit Co.\u20141937 common\nshare earnings before surtax were\n$3.24, against $2.39.\nMead Johnson Co.\u2014Declared 75\ncents extra and 75 cents quarterly\ncommon dividends, payable April 1\nto holders of record March 15.\nGrant, W. T., Co.\u2014Common share\nearnings after surtax, year ended\nJanuary 31, were $2.75, against $3.84.\nPenney, J. C., Co.\u20141937 common\nshare earnings before surtax were\n$6.61, against $7.37.\nUnited Drug, Inc.\u20141937 common\nshare earnings were 94 cents, against\n$1.52.\nEastern Gas Fuel Associates\u2014\n1937 preliminary net income was\n$3,017,816, against $2,877,031. Net in\ncome, 12 months ended January 31,\n1938, was $3,095,646, against $2,725,\n611.\nEagle-Picher Lead Co.\u20141937 com\nmon share earnings were 40 cents,\nagainst 74 cents.\nNew York Central R. R.\u2014Company\nannounced a reduction to 25 cents\nfor pleasure cars on West Shore ferries\nbetween New York and Weehawken.\nYoungstown Sheet Tube Co.\u2014It\nis said this company has negotiated\na loan with bank believed to involve\naround $12,500,000. Of the total it is\nbelieved about $5,000,000 will be used\nto pay off previous loans, and remain\nder will be added to cash.\nAmerican Telephone Telegraph\nCo.\u2014Station gain by Bell system in\nFebruary totaled 30,000 telephones,\nagainst 92,000 in February, 1937. In\nJanuary, 1938, net increase was 31,500.\nBell Telephone Co. of Pennsylva\nnia\u2014Station gain in February totaled\n1,752, against 10,282 in February; 1937.\nIn two months station gain was 4,499,\nagainst 19,230.\nBrooklyn Union Oas Co.\u2014Company\ncurrently has outstanding $2,750,000\nin notes due banks, against $3,750,000\non December 31, 1937. January and\nFebruary gas send-out of company was\n10 per cent larger than in the like\n1937 period. Earnings in first month\nof 1938 amounted to 6 cents a share.\nLIVE STOCK PRICES\nHIT YEWPEAKS\nNew Highs Are Established\nas Result of Sharp Curb\non Supplies.\nThe following review of the live\nstock market for the week ended\nMarch 3 was prepared for the As\nsociated Press by the United States\nDepartment of Agriculture:\nCHICAGO, March 5.\u2014Sellers and\nproducers were In a favorable position\nthis week and were successful In rais\ning all species of live stock to the\nhighest level of the year to date. Sup\nply abridgment provided the leverage\nwith which the selling side boosted\nprices measurably, despite little im\nprovement in wholesale meat trade\nconditions. Fed steers gained 25 to\n50 cents during the week, fat lambs\nmade 50 to 75 cent upturns and hogs\nscored advances ranging from 25 to\n75 cents.\nThe supply of cattle was almost up\nto last week's volume, but hog and\nlamb marketings fell off sharply, the\ndecrease at seven major markets ap\nproximating 51,000 hogs and 25,000\nsheep and lambs. Not only fed steers\nand yearlings, but all other grades\nand classes of cattle sold higher at\nChicago, and at most times the trade\nwas active at the advance. Steers and\nheifers predominated- in the week's\nsupply, and best weighty steers made\n10.35 at Chicago, with yearlings at\n9.90 and weighty heifers, 8.75. Most\nof the steer crop sold late in the week\nat 7.50-9.00.\nWholesale meat markets failed to\nkeep pace with advancing live costs,\nand successive upturns brought buying\nresistance from sources where cut out\nreturns were unfavorable.\nHog Prices Boosted.\nAbridged marketings enabled the\nselling side to boost hog prices to the\nhighest point of the year and top price\nat Chicago to the highest peak since\nearly .in November, 1937. Weighty\nbutchers moved upward to further\ncontract the price spread between\nlight and heavy hogs. At Chicago 185\n215-pound hogs sold up to 9.60 Thurs\nday, with bulk sales of 160-260-pound\naverages at 9.35-9.55. Comparable\n270-375-pound butchers sold at 8.90\n9.35.\nFat Lambs Above $9.\nFat lambs passed the 9.00 line at\ni Chicago, the top Thursday standing\nat 9.20, with most late sales of good\nand choice offerings at 8.75-9.00.\nBest lambs sold more dependably\nat Kansas City than at any time in\nrecent weeks, the top going to 8.50,\nwith late sales largely 8.00-8.40.\nChoice fed, wooled lambs sold up to\n8.75 at Omaha and a peak of 8.85\nwas paid Thursday at Sioux City.\n\nWashington Exchange\nSALES.\nCapital Transit Co.\u201414 at 8.\nWashington Gas Lt. pfd.\u201410 at 10054,\n10 at 1005,, 10 at 100>4.\nBid and Asked Prices.\nBONDS.\nPUBLIC UTILITY.\nBid. Asked.\nAnacostia Pot os _ 56 60\nAna. Pot. Guar, 6s_107 _\nC. P. Tel. of Va 6s_106 _\nCan. Traction R. R. 5s_ 68 72\nCity A Suburban 5s _ 58 63\nGeorgetown Gas 1st 5s_113\nPot. Elec. Pow 3>\u00abs_104 106\nWash. Gas 5s 1058_104*2 105*4\nWash. Gas 5s 1060. _115\nWash. Rwy. A Elec. 4s... lOO3. _\nMISCELLANEOUS.\nChevy Chase Club 1st 4*/,s. 104 _\nCol. Country Club 1st 454s. 103 _\nW. M. Cold Storage 5s 100 _\nSTOCKS.\nPUBLIC UTILITY.\nAmer Tel Tel (9) 135*4\nCapital Transit Co __ _ bs 8*