ains Limited\nMostly to Fractions.\nSteels Improve.\nStock Averages\n30 15 15 00\nInduBt. Ralls. Util. Stocks.\nNet change. t\u2014.1 \u2014.2 \u2014.1 \u2014.1\nToday, close 64.2 19.1 31.0 44.5\nPrevious day 64.3 19.3 31.1 44.6\nMonth ago.. 61.9 18.1 30.7 43.0\nYear ago...101.5 47.4 50.3 76.0\n1938 high_ 68.2 21.6 34.9 47.9\n1938 low_ 59.2 17.6 30.0 41.3\n1937 high_101.6 49.5 54.0 75.3\n1937 low_ 57.7 19.0 31.6 41.7\n1932 low_ 17.5 8.7 23.9 16.9\n1929 high_146.9 153.9 184.3 157.7\n1927 low_ 51.6 95.3 61.8 61.8\n(Complied by the Associated Press.)\nBy VICTOR EUBANK,\nAssociated Press Financial Writer.\nNEW YORK, March 5 \u2014Stocks pre\nsented a moderately ragged appearance\nIn today's market.\nDealings again were of extremelv\nsmall proportions and losses and gains\ngenerally held to minor fractions.\nA few steels and coppers displayed\noccasional rallying inclinations, but\nmost utilities, rails, rubbers, mail\norders and aircrafts were virtually at\na standstill.\nSuch selling as presented itself was\ntermed by brokers \u2022\u2018unimportant,\" as\nwas the buying.\nTraders apparently continued to\nlimit participations pending more\ndefinite information regarding the\nultimate text of the tax revision meas\nure now before Congress. The delay\nin the freight rate decision was also\nseen as a deterrent to speculative ac\ntivity.\nBusiness news was spotty and even\nscattered optimistic items failed to\nbuoy market sentiment to any notice\nable extent.\nTransfers were in the neighborhood\nof 250.000 shares for the 2-hour ses\nsion.\nWoolworth, exhibiting strength\nlately, moved narrowly, although the\ncompany reported January-February\nsales were 2.9 per cent over the same\nperiod a year ago.\nBorg-Wamer was an isolated weak\nissue, losing about 2 points at the\nworst, following action of directors in\nomitting the dividend on the common\nThe reason given was that present\nsales and the immediate general out\nlook did not warrant a payment at\nthis time.\nResistant stocks included United\nStates Steel, Bethlehem, Republic,\nYoungstown, General Motors, General\nElectric, American Can. United States\nRubber, Sears Roebuck, Anaconda,\nCerro de Pasco. Santa Fe. Chesapeake\nOhio and North American.\nBackward were Chrysler, Crucible\nSteel. Du Pont. Seaboard Oil, Amer\nican Telephone. Philip Morris, Union\nCarbide and Corn Products.\nBALTIMORE STOCKS\nSi ectal Dispatch to The Star.\nBALTIMORE March ft\nSa r.'h arSTPwiS' High. Low. Close.\n60 Arundel Corp _ I53\u00bb 153. lsa.\nBalt Transit 34 a! 15a\"\n\u25a0o Con Pow fto pf A lift m m\n200Eastn Sug As vt 6 6 ii\nn Fidelity A: Dep 9h34 9rt34 ptia4\n1 On Mar Tex Oil Co \"i.\nJMt Ver Wd Mills \"'i\nft. New Amster Cas 10\u2019. in3, liii,\n109 U S Fidel Guar {yi*\nFOREIGN MARKETS.\nm yV0RPO9L-. M\u00bbrch 5 (Pi.\u2014Wheat fu\ntures moved down \u20182 to 34d today in\nP^hany with North American rackets\nthe day before. However, final prices\n*\u00a3re ,be*,er than expected owing to an\nofficial Argentine government report of\ninV*h^f.?haat ln iec,eiDt from the north\nprotein gradedemand f0r Amencan high\nc,osed duiet. unchanged to\npdjots lower. Easiness in New York yes\nL\"day 7\u2019fntiPffset by steady Eastern mar\nJ?,\u00a3\u2022 A httle speculative selling met trade\nPal;i\"? ar'd Ideal support, the latter en\ncouraged by scarcity of contracts.\nLondon and Paris closed.\nMoney for Construction Loans\nand\nLoans on Existing Properties\n5%\nFIR8T DEED OF TRUST ONLI\nGEORGE I. B0R6ER\n643 Indiana Are. N.W.\nNat\u2019l 0350\nConservative\nFirst Mortgage\nInvestments\nSecured on New Homes\nPaying 5\u2019/2% 'nterft I\nAvailable March ISth\nChas. D. Sager\nSince 1910\n924 14th N.W. National 0036\nREFINANCE\nYOUR HOME\nby\nLONG TERM\nReal Estate\nJoauL\n5%\nNo Renewal Fees.\nInterest Only on Un\npaid Balance.\n-fa Also F. H. A.; 3-year\nStraight and Con\nstruction Loans.\nD. C. and Nearby\nMd. and Va. Prop\nerty.\nLOAN Correspondent\nTRAVELERS INSURANCE\nCOMPANY\nH.G. Smithy Co.\n81115th